Stay Safe Online: Prevention Checklist

General Digital Safety

1. Enable Two-Factor Authentication (2FA): Use app-based authenticators (like Google Authenticator) for your VIT Gmail, GitHub, and LinkedIn accounts rather than just SMS.

2. Secure Your Webcam: Use a physical slider or a small piece of tape over your laptop camera when not in use to prevent "cam-fecting" via malware.

3. Use a Password Manager: Avoid using "VIT@123" or similar easy-to-guess passwords. Use a manager to generate and store unique, 16-character passwords for every site.

4. Verify Official Emails: Always check the sender’s domain. Official VIT communication will always come from @vit.ac.in, never from a generic @gmail.com or @outlook.com address.

5. Beware of Public Wi-Fi: Avoid logging into bank accounts or your Student Login portal while on unsecured public Wi-Fi (like at cafes or airports) without a VPN.

6. Think Before You Click: Hover over links in emails to see the actual destination URL before clicking to avoid sophisticated phishing clones of login pages.

Financial & UPI Safety (India Specific)

7. The Golden Rule of UPI: Remember that entering your UPI PIN is ONLY for sending money. You never need to enter a PIN, scan a QR code, or "Accept" a request to receive money.

8. Check the 'Verified' Badge: Before paying a local merchant or an online seller via UPI, verify the name displayed on the screen matches the person or business you are dealing with.

🚨 How to Report Cybercrime in India
If you or a peer have been a victim of a digital or financial scam:

National Cyber Crime Reporting Portal: cybercrime.gov.in

National Helpline Number: Call 1930 immediately (especially for financial fraud to trigger a "Golden Hour" transaction freeze).
